00:14:15,920 --> 00:14:20,440
had with the team I had and I turned it into this 
thing that was going to be something we wanted. 

184
00:14:20,440 --> 00:14:26,040
And so I think sometimes it's not... I think that 
that experience was a very humbling experience  

185
00:14:26,040 --> 00:14:31,120
because to be told no and then to say that 
this will never happen was really hard. But  

186
00:14:31,120 --> 00:14:35,360
at the same time it was a reminder that you're 
not right for every job even if you think you  

187
00:14:35,360 --> 00:14:40,520
are. And that you can take the raw materials of 
what you have and turn it into what you want.

188
00:14:40,520 --> 00:14:44,360
Are you able to share what those jobs were 
that you wanted to get that you never got?

189
00:14:44,360 --> 00:14:50,080
I never actually shared it publicly, but it's 
something which I had always had a role where  

190
00:14:50,080 --> 00:14:54,560
I did new things for the company and there was a 
role where it was running something which more of  

191
00:14:54,560 --> 00:14:59,480
an existing business, but I had always been kind 
of the innovator, the new stuff person. I had  

192
00:14:59,480 --> 00:15:04,680
taken over so many new things. And so maybe that 
wasn't the right thing at the right time for me,  

193
00:15:04,680 --> 00:15:08,240
but it was something that was really 
incredible and a turning point for me.

194
00:15:08,240 --> 00:15:13,240
Great segue to an area I wanted to spend some time 
on which is building zero to one stuff within a  

195
00:15:13,240 --> 00:15:20,280
larger company. So from what I can tell you built 
2 billion businesses within a large company,  

196
00:15:20,280 --> 00:15:25,840
Facebook marketplace, and then the ads platform 
within Facebook and maybe more. I don't know,  

197
00:15:25,840 --> 00:15:28,720
the payments stuff, the games. I don't 
know. Maybe there's billions of dollars  

198
00:15:28,720 --> 00:15:33,640
there I don't even know about. And 
this is very rare and very hard,  

199
00:15:33,640 --> 00:15:38,040
and it's something we talk a little bit on this 
podcast, just the skills to build something new. 

200
00:15:38,040 --> 00:15:41,600
I know with marketplace it was not something 
people believed in for a long time. It took  

201
00:15:41,600 --> 00:15:46,200
a lot of work to convince people to actually 
give it a shot. So I guess the question here  

202
00:15:46,200 --> 00:15:52,640
is just what have you found are key tactics to 
start something new and allow it to continue to  

203
00:15:52,640 --> 00:15:57,640
exist and get to a place where people start 
to believe it? What has worked for you?

204
00:15:57,640 --> 00:16:01,680
So first, I didn't build the ads platform. I 
actually built the first direct response ad  

205
00:16:01,680 --> 00:16:08,360
product company ever had. But we'll talk about how 
that led to why direct response is a vast majority  

206
00:16:08,360 --> 00:16:15,440
of the ads revenue for the company. But one thing 
that it was really interesting is that I really  

207
00:16:15,440 --> 00:16:19,360
saw my opportunity in Facebook to be somebody 
that zigged when other people zagged. There  

208
00:16:19,360 --> 00:16:24,640
were amazing people who did a lot of the really 
core products working on feed, photos, videos. 

209
00:16:26,200 --> 00:16:30,680
I came in actually on the payments team and we 
worked on payments and eventually built games,  

210
00:16:30,680 --> 00:16:34,280
which was the first billion dollar business. 
It was very successful. We worked with the  

211
00:16:34,280 --> 00:16:38,520
likes of all the game companies that 
were on the Canvas games platform.  

212
00:16:38,520 --> 00:16:42,200
And it was just an incredible opportunity 
to start from scratch and built something  

213
00:16:42,200 --> 00:16:48,000
really cool. We built Facebook credits, which 
eventually became the Facebook payment system. 

214
00:16:48,000 --> 00:16:53,400
And then from there on I built the first 
direct response ads product. And again,  

215
00:16:53,400 --> 00:16:57,040
leveraging the skills that we had, we had 
a lot of relationships with game companies  

216
00:16:57,040 --> 00:16:59,800
because of my time and payments. 
And so we just said, "Hey look,  

217
00:16:59,800 --> 00:17:04,640
what ad product do you want?" And they said, 
"Actually, your biggest challenge is the shift  

218
00:17:04,640 --> 00:17:09,600
to mobile. Build us a mobile acquisition 
engine." And we said, "That's doable." 

219
00:17:09,600 --> 00:17:13,640
At the time the company was very brand oriented. 
Most of the ads... Actually almost all the ads  

220
00:17:13,640 --> 00:17:17,480
on the platform were brand and we were not even 
on the ads team. So we actually worked on this  

221
00:17:17,480 --> 00:17:23,400
team called the platform team. We said, "Okay, 
we'll build an ads product for the Facebook feed,  

222
00:17:23,400 --> 00:17:27,080
the new mobile Facebook feed." And suddenly it 
became a billion dollar business within about 18  

223
00:17:27,080 --> 00:17:33,040
months, which was such an incredible journey.
We worked on the mobile advertising platform,  

224
00:17:33,040 --> 00:17:38,280
so basically the mobile ads network. That was a 
great experience. And so each time I worked on  

225
00:17:38,280 --> 00:17:43,240
something, it was just... The thing that you have 
to remember is the failure rate for something like  

226
00:17:43,240 --> 00:17:48,760
this is very high. You start something and the 
amount of iteration... People think, "Oh yeah,  

227
00:17:48,760 --> 00:17:52,520
it's easy." You start something and it's linear 
because you have all the resources of this company  

228
00:17:52,520 --> 00:17:58,280
behind you. But actually everything in the company 
is like, "Let's do the most important thing." 

229
00:17:58,280 --> 00:18:03,640
These are seeds and we'll just let them... And 
so if you do that, you have to know that you  

230
00:18:03,640 --> 00:18:07,400
don't get a lot of resources, you get a lot 
of attention. And I appreciated that because  

231
00:18:07,400 --> 00:18:13,000
I think I work best when people aren't... There 
is not a lot of scrutiny. I think sometimes large  

232
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:16,160
companies, they say, "Well this innovation 
team," and then they check in on them way  

233
00:18:16,160 --> 00:18:20,840
too much. They're like, "Week to week progress, 
where are you going? What's your strategy?" But  

234
00:18:20,840 --> 00:18:27,400
so much as you know of building something new is 
the iteration process. It's the failing a lot. 

235
00:18:27,400 --> 00:18:33,000
We actually tested five or six versions of the 
ads product before we got it to take off and it  

236
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:36,840
took months, and then we were on the verge of 
death multiple times. In fact, I actually went  

237
00:18:36,840 --> 00:18:41,160
back to run the payments team while I was working 
on that product because the team we had gathered  

238
00:18:41,160 --> 00:18:45,880
still want to continue working on it, but I 
needed a second job back on the payments team  

239
00:18:45,880 --> 00:18:49,880
because they asked me, "We don't think this thing 
is going to work. You should go run your old team  

240
00:18:49,880 --> 00:18:54,480
again." And I thought, "Well, I will do both."
And so I did both for a while until it really  

241
00:18:54,480 --> 00:18:59,640
took off. The thing that I think a lot of 
large companies don't realize is that you  

242
00:18:59,640 --> 00:19:07,040
can love something to death. And so with every new 
product, I'd rather do it out of the limelight,  

243
00:19:07,040 --> 00:19:13,200
do it with the minimal resources and have the 
freedom to fail because success and failure  

244
00:19:13,200 --> 00:19:18,480
really is... In startups, failing fast 
is really important or succeeding fast. 

245
00:19:18,480 --> 00:19:23,120
It's the long slog that makes it really hard. In 
a company, you end up getting cut if you're the  

246
00:19:23,120 --> 00:19:27,440
long slog product. And so being able to just say, 
"You know what? We're pruning this. We're doing  

247
00:19:27,440 --> 00:19:33,720
the next thing, the next thing." And then having 
the time to iterate and grow is really critical.

248
00:19:33,720 --> 00:19:39,160
So as a leader trying to do this and create space 
for this, is there something you've learned about  

249
00:19:39,160 --> 00:19:45,320
how to allow for, "Don't over scrutinize us, 
don't look at us too carefully. We don't want  

250
00:19:45,320 --> 00:19:49,440
to be in the limelight. Don't put too many 
resources on this yet." Is it just like, "Hey,  

251
00:19:49,440 --> 00:19:54,480
Mark. Here's what I think." I imagine it's not 
as easy as that. There's a lot of influence and  

252
00:19:54,480 --> 00:19:58,640
that kind of work. Is there any tactics that you 
could share to create this sort of environment?

253
00:19:59,480 --> 00:20:05,080
I think the most important part of the 
environment is really patience. And again,  

254
00:20:05,080 --> 00:20:10,360
this is a portfolio strategy and I tell every PM 
who... I used to do a new hire PM class and I say,  

255
00:20:10,360 --> 00:20:15,400
"Look, a lot of you are going to go into the 
core product and your job is to grow X by 3  

256
00:20:15,400 --> 00:20:21,880
to 5% every six months. Growing engagement or 
growing sessions or maybe growing video views  

257
00:20:21,880 --> 00:20:27,320
or whatever your metric is, you're trying to grow 
something 5% and then you exceed expectations." 

258
00:20:27,320 --> 00:20:30,400
And I said, "And then a bunch of you are 
like, 'I want to do something new. I want  

259
00:20:30,400 --> 00:20:33,800
to build something from scratch.'" 
And I said, "By the way, a very,  

260
00:20:33,800 --> 00:20:39,840
very successful company for a new set of 
products has a 50% hit rate. So half of  

261
00:20:39,840 --> 00:20:45,520
you are going to come back in a year and have a 
different job because that did not work out. Do  

262
00:20:45,520 --> 00:20:51,800
you have the resilience to do that?" And I think 
somebody, you enter a large company... By the way,  

263
00:20:51,800 --> 00:20:56,320
you can have an amazing career building core 
products because that is an incredible journey  

264
00:20:56,320 --> 00:20:59,640
within... Because you learn so much 
about the mechanics of what that takes. 

265
00:20:59,640 --> 00:21:03,640
And yet at the same time, I found a lot of 
energy from doing something that someone  

266
00:21:03,640 --> 00:21:08,880
hasn't done before. And so I really enjoyed the, 
"Hey, this thing could fail. Let's pivot. Let's  

267
00:21:08,880 --> 00:21:13,600
try to figure out. Let's prune this. Let's try 
that." And not everything I did there succeeded,  

268
00:21:13,600 --> 00:21:19,680
but a lot of the things that are the lasting 
products are once that gotten really big. And  

269
00:21:19,680 --> 00:21:24,320
so for me it was a greater reward and it 
made a journey so much more interesting. 

270
00:21:24,320 --> 00:21:28,680
But for others, I think work on the core 
product, learn the skills. It is absolutely  

271
00:21:28,680 --> 00:21:33,120
respectable as well. But if you choose to be 
the person who works on innovation new products,  

272
00:21:33,120 --> 00:21:36,880
expect in a year, you might literally have 
nothing to show for it, but the lessons that  

273
00:21:36,880 --> 00:21:42,240
you learned. And I think those lessons are really 
precious and we often underestimate that too.

274
00:21:42,240 --> 00:21:47,120
Along those lines, do you think it's a 
good career move to do a zero to one thing  

275
00:21:47,120 --> 00:21:52,080
within a bigger company? Or is it often a bad 
idea? Do you have any advice there for folks?

276
00:21:52,080 --> 00:21:56,040
It depends. It depends on your personality 
in the company. So the one thing I realized  

277
00:21:56,040 --> 00:22:01,640
about my role was that I did a lot of... I 
had five different careers at the company  

278
00:22:01,640 --> 00:22:05,160
over 11 years. And so most people don't 
realize that when you work on new things,  

279
00:22:05,160 --> 00:22:09,120
you're constantly adding to your portfolio, 
subtracting from it, growing things, pruning  

280
00:22:09,120 --> 00:22:16,520
them. And so you could just work on so many cool 
things except everything has similar... It's  

281
00:22:16,520 --> 00:22:20,920
like it rhymes, but it's not exactly the same.
So you learn the lessons of how to get things  

282
00:22:20,920 --> 00:22:25,920
done, how to get resource, how to get support 
when the product is not working, how to not get  

283
00:22:25,920 --> 00:22:32,080
prunes in the next culling. And those are really, 
really important skills. But I think for people  

284
00:22:32,080 --> 00:22:35,560
who are just starting out of the career, it is 
a very high risk thing to do. So if you're very  

285
00:22:35,560 --> 00:22:39,600
early in the career, I encourage people just 
learn the core skills first. You can learn the  

286
00:22:39,600 --> 00:22:44,760
core skills when there's a lot of stability. This 
product is growing X percent, like 5%, and you're  

287
00:22:44,760 --> 00:22:48,880
going to grow at 10. That's amazing.
That is because you are there, you're  

288
00:22:48,880 --> 00:22:55,120
going to change your trajectory of the product, 
or this thing has a hundred thousand users,  

289
00:22:55,120 --> 00:23:01,240
you're going to get it to 200,000. Those are the 
kinds of things that are going to be successful  

290
00:23:01,240 --> 00:23:05,080
for you and you can put on your resume. But I 
think it reaches a point in your career where  

291
00:23:05,080 --> 00:23:08,920
you have to decide, when am I going to take 
the big swing? Because the big swings are  

292
00:23:08,920 --> 00:23:14,480
the things that you write your career stories 
about. They're not just, I moved this metric X,  

293
00:23:14,480 --> 00:23:20,000
but I changed your trajectory in this way.
And so the big swings though have a lot of  

294
00:23:20,000 --> 00:23:24,440
failures along the way. And so you have 
to understand you're making trade-offs in  

295
00:23:24,440 --> 00:23:28,120
that. I encourage everybody to take some time, 
two, three years in their career when they're  

296
00:23:28,120 --> 00:23:33,360
ready for the big swing, where if it doesn't 
work... If it works, you run the team, you run  

297
00:23:33,360 --> 00:23:39,440
this amazing product. It doesn't work, you can 
always go back and go back to the core products.

298
00:23:39,440 --> 00:23:43,440
It's interesting how your strategy here 
is very similar to a product portfolio  

299
00:23:43,440 --> 00:23:48,560
strategy where as a team should have a few 
big bets and then a lot of incremental stuff.  

300
00:23:48,560 --> 00:23:52,360
And it reminds me about this awesome post 
called You Are in Control of Your Career.  

301
00:23:52,360 --> 00:23:56,960
And the argument in your post is you should 
PM your career the way you PM your product.  

302
00:23:56,960 --> 00:24:01,240
So there's a lot of synergy here. So maybe just 
diving into this post and advice around this,  

303
00:24:01,240 --> 00:24:05,520
how should someone be PMing their career, the 
way they PM a product? What's your take there?

304
00:24:05,520 --> 00:24:09,840
By the way, for your PM audience, I want to 
say this, which is a lot of the greatest PMs  

305
00:24:09,840 --> 00:24:15,680
are the worst PMs of their careers. They love 
products. They love the crafts. They love the  

306
00:24:15,680 --> 00:24:20,680
customer research, the data. They have plans, they 
have timelines. And then when it comes to career,  

307
00:24:20,680 --> 00:24:24,800
they have none of those things. They just drift 
from job to job. "Hey, should I take this role  

308
00:24:24,800 --> 00:24:30,840
or this role? How do I think about this?" But if 
I said you had to write a spec for your career,  

309
00:24:30,840 --> 00:24:35,400
what's in there? What are your milestones? 
What are the skills? What are the features  

310
00:24:35,400 --> 00:24:41,000
that you want to have of your career? How are you 
going to get there? What does success look like? 

311
00:24:41,000 --> 00:24:47,320
You actually have metrics for your product, and 
yet you don't have metrics for your career. I  

312
00:24:47,320 --> 00:24:51,240
coach a lot of people and when I coach them, I ask 
them, "Well, where do you want to see yourself in  

313
00:24:51,240 --> 00:24:57,240
five years? Where do you want to go?" And half the 
people have no idea. I think that's really tragic  

314
00:24:57,240 --> 00:25:01,560
because when you PM your career, it's about 
intentionality. But I'll tell you the story  

315
00:25:01,560 --> 00:25:06,120
of my career and how I was the accidental PM and 
then eventually... I told you how I accidentally  

316
00:25:06,120 --> 00:25:10,320
fell into PM, but also fell into so many of 
the things that happened in my PM career. 

317
00:25:10,320 --> 00:25:14,120
And if I had to go back, I would think much 
more deeply about what I want to accomplish.  

318
00:25:14,120 --> 00:25:18,640
So I ended up at PayPal working for a guy 
named Dave Lee who reported to Amy Clement,  

319
00:25:18,640 --> 00:25:24,520
and then he left. And so she offered me his role. 
I had only managed people for, I don't know,  

320
00:25:24,520 --> 00:25:29,520
15 seconds. I was two years out of business school 
and I was definitely not qualified to do his job.  

321
00:25:29,520 --> 00:25:34,600
He was the director of product. I wasn't even 
a director and I was running the team for eBay. 

322
00:25:34,600 --> 00:25:40,520
So basically the PayPal part of eBay, which 
was basically half the company's revenues and  

323
00:25:40,520 --> 00:25:47,880
profits. Totally unqualified. I ended up in this 
job and I do a good job. I ended up doing it for  

324
00:25:47,880 --> 00:25:53,720
several years. I built up the team and we have a 
great relationship with eBay. Our team was very  

325
00:25:53,720 --> 00:25:58,400
close and we were able to actually build something 
really lasting that worked really well. And then  

326
00:25:58,400 --> 00:26:05,160
I had a baby. And so this happens in a lot of 
women's careers. I was turning 30, I had my son,  

327
00:26:05,160 --> 00:26:10,560
and I had to leave for six months.
So I handed my product to my successor,  

328
00:26:10,560 --> 00:26:14,640
Mike Woo and he ended up taking over. 
He did such a good job while I was gone,  

329
00:26:14,640 --> 00:26:17,480
I didn't want to displace him when 
I got back. And so I thought, "Well,  

330
00:26:17,480 --> 00:26:21,200
I'll go and look for another role." I couldn't 
really find a product role I liked, I mean,  

331
00:26:21,200 --> 00:26:26,000
because there weren't that many product director 
roles. And so I ended up in corporate strategy. So  

332
00:26:26,000 --> 00:26:31,240
I worked for the amazing Rajiv who was CEO at the 
time. He since passed and I wrote his speeches,  

333
00:26:31,240 --> 00:26:35,600
worked on strategies, I worked on digital 
goods and charity, and ended up building  

334
00:26:35,600 --> 00:26:40,440
that into a vertical for the company. So 
charity, social commerce and digital goods. 

335
00:26:40,440 --> 00:26:43,280
And I thought, "Okay, this is an 
interesting job." So I create the job,  

336
00:26:43,280 --> 00:26:47,600
have a couple product managers, wasn't really sure 
where this was going, and then one day I was like,  

337
00:26:47,600 --> 00:26:53,560
"You know what? I'm not feeling this. I have a 
child at home." I had gotten into what Cheryl  

338
00:26:53,560 --> 00:26:57,520
Sandberg calls that kind of between kids 
situation where I was bored of my job. 

339
00:26:57,520 --> 00:27:04,640
I was working one of the VPs I worked with 
and I resigned. I said, "I'm leaving tech,  

340
00:27:04,640 --> 00:27:09,920
just I'm going to stay home and maybe start 
something small." He convinced me to hold off  

341
00:27:09,920 --> 00:27:14,320
and he said, I'll find you a job. He calls 
me a week later and he said, "Found you a  

342
00:27:14,320 --> 00:27:19,800
job with Stephanie Tilenius leading the buyer 
experience at eBay product." And I said, "Oh,  

343
00:27:19,800 --> 00:27:24,720
that sounds interesting." So I said, "Sure, as you 
notice, I do not have a plan. I'm just drifting.  

344
00:27:25,400 --> 00:27:31,800
I'm so fortunate that I had amazing mentors who 
gave me opportunities, but end up working for Greg  

345
00:27:31,800 --> 00:27:36,200
Fant and Stephanie Tilenius at eBay for two years.
I led the buyer experience. We did some really  

346
00:27:36,200 --> 00:27:41,400
good work there. And then went on maternity 
leave again. And I get a call from a friend,  

347
00:27:41,400 --> 00:27:46,280
my old engineering manager from PayPal, "Hey, I'm 
at Facebook. Do you want to come? You can't come  

348
00:27:46,280 --> 00:27:50,800
into product. You need a CS degree for that, but 
we have a product marketing job open." I was like,  

349
00:27:50,800 --> 00:27:57,280
"Sounds good." Drop into Facebook. And so again, 
no idea what I'm doing back in product marketing.  

350
00:27:57,280 --> 00:28:02,720
So I spent a few years doing that. Eventually 
was invited into product and so on and so forth. 

351
00:28:02,720 --> 00:28:08,640
And each job that came along was organic, but also 
kind of accidental. I see that happen in a lot of  

352
00:28:08,640 --> 00:28:14,480
careers, which is my story when you look back, 
looks great. It looks like it all worked out,  

353
00:28:14,480 --> 00:28:18,920
but I had almost zero intentionality 
in any of these. And I think that had  

354
00:28:18,920 --> 00:28:22,840
I had more agency and I thought about what 
I wanted, I could actually measure is this  

355
00:28:22,840 --> 00:28:27,680
the thing that would get me further or not?
I ended up extremely lucky, but not everybody  

356
00:28:27,680 --> 00:28:34,240
does. And so I think having a plan allows you to 
compare every decision. It's not like when you're  

357
00:28:34,240 --> 00:28:40,360
offered an admission to college, we're looking 
at three different offers maybe with financial  

358
00:28:40,360 --> 00:28:43,600
aid or not, and you can make a decision, 
"Oh, they're offering me this department,  

359
00:28:43,600 --> 00:28:49,960
but I can't get into this department." This is 
how far it is from home. But jobs and roles or  

360
00:28:49,960 --> 00:28:54,720
nothing like that. Someone calls you one day, 
"Hey, I'm at Facebook. Do you want to come? I'm  

361
00:28:55,320 --> 00:29:00,760
actually on maternity leave." And he's like, 
"Just come talk to me." I'm like, "Why not." 

362
