00:46:17,920 --> 00:46:22,840
little bit. You have a really nice perspective on 
how to think about growth. I think a lot of people  

588
00:46:22,840 --> 00:46:26,360
think of growth as like, "Here's a magic bullet. 
We're going to do this thing. It's going to go,  

589
00:46:26,360 --> 00:46:29,760
"Wow, we're going to win." And your 
approach is, you talk about it, it's a  

590
00:46:29,760 --> 00:46:34,080
game of inches. Growth is a game of inches. 
Can you talk about your perspective there?

591
00:46:34,080 --> 00:46:39,880
Yeah. Sometimes we think it's like what is the 
huge step function? But actually most companies  

592
00:46:39,880 --> 00:46:44,840
are like... We call it points of growth, right? 
It's like if you can move things 1% a little  

593
00:46:44,840 --> 00:46:49,560
bit faster every single week, think about the 
amount of growth you get at the end. And so  

594
00:46:49,560 --> 00:46:56,400
it's not just, "Okay, what's going to get you the 
3X? You can get to 3X 1% at a time, 5% at a time.  

595
00:46:56,400 --> 00:47:02,400
Single digit growth. And sometimes it is the small 
things that matter the most. And so we think about  

596
00:47:02,400 --> 00:47:08,040
product-led growth, it's really about finding 
the aha moments, the opportunities. And sometimes  

597
00:47:08,040 --> 00:47:12,920
opportunities are things that seem really silly.
I heard the story at Facebook that one of the big  

598
00:47:12,920 --> 00:47:17,680
things was just adding the, next to 
ads, they put the word create an ad,  

599
00:47:17,680 --> 00:47:22,240
was one of the biggest growth drivers. And that 
was it just putting a link because people just  

600
00:47:22,240 --> 00:47:28,560
didn't know how to get to the ads flow. It was 
things like that where you can actually bend the  

601
00:47:28,560 --> 00:47:33,800
curve of choices that you make. Same thing, each 
of the growth teams I've ever worked on, it's like  

602
00:47:33,800 --> 00:47:38,800
really the small things adding up. It is a list we 
used to work on payments growth and we had a list  

603
00:47:38,800 --> 00:47:44,440
of a hundred things we were working on hypotheses.
And then we would pick and we would grow them by  

604
00:47:44,440 --> 00:47:47,840
picking the first 10 and we would start working 
on them, the next 10, the next 10, and we would  

605
00:47:47,840 --> 00:47:51,480
go through these sprint cycles. And the same 
thing when we were growing the ads product as  

606
00:47:51,480 --> 00:47:57,040
well. Marketplace, each of them were just like, 
"What are the small things that add up to big  

607
00:47:57,040 --> 00:48:03,040
things?" And I think sometimes we overthink it.
Instead, you probably have a hundred ideas. And  

608
00:48:03,040 --> 00:48:09,440
by the way, it is absolutely okay if the 80% 
of them don't work. I tell people sometimes  

609
00:48:09,440 --> 00:48:14,200
we overthink as product manager if we just had the 
perfect plan, the perfect battle plan, but instead  

610
00:48:14,200 --> 00:48:19,960
imagine you're a team and you can ship, I don't 
know, let's say four things. But what if you're  

611
00:48:19,960 --> 00:48:27,160
a team that can ship 20 things with the same 
with a 20% success. You get just as much output  

612
00:48:27,160 --> 00:48:32,800
and yet you know what doesn't work also.
What if you can move it from 20% to 30%?  

613
00:48:32,800 --> 00:48:36,960
Suddenly six things work, not just four things. 
And so in the same amount of time you have all  

614
00:48:36,960 --> 00:48:41,040
the lessons of what didn't work, plus you're 
getting 50% more output. And so you thinking  

615
00:48:41,040 --> 00:48:45,800
about growth as this engine of, it's a 
learning machine of what doesn't work,  

616
00:48:45,800 --> 00:48:50,520
what you reiterate on, what you change, and you're 
constantly getting better and better and better.

617
00:48:50,520 --> 00:48:53,760
I think what you're saying will resonate 
with a lot of product people where there's  

618
00:48:53,760 --> 00:48:57,920
always this like, "We're just doing a bunch of 
optimization, incremental work. Still sucks,  

619
00:48:57,920 --> 00:49:04,200
boring. Let's take some big bets." And in my 
experience, and sounds like in your experience,  

620
00:49:04,200 --> 00:49:08,920
a lot of the wins actually... And Facebook 
is famous for this, just relentlessly looking  

621
00:49:08,920 --> 00:49:14,560
for ways to grow, optimize, optimize, optimize 
because that's where a lot of growth comes from. 

622
00:49:14,560 --> 00:49:17,840
At the same time, obviously you need to 
take some big bets and take some swings  

623
00:49:17,840 --> 00:49:22,000
and look for step function changes. But 
I guess for someone that's just like...  

624
00:49:22,000 --> 00:49:24,160
I don't know. Is there any advice on 
just creating that culture of like,  

625
00:49:24,160 --> 00:49:27,640
"It's okay to optimize for a long time, there's 
a lot of opportunity optimizing"? Is there  

626
00:49:27,640 --> 00:49:32,400
anything you've learned there or is it just 
bringing in a Deb and it has to be a top down?

627
00:49:32,400 --> 00:49:36,720
I treat growth like, let's say, 
a product marketing team. It is  

628
00:49:36,720 --> 00:49:40,280
an augmentation for a product that works. 
So if you have a core product that works,  

629
00:49:40,280 --> 00:49:44,080
you have a team that's working on... So for us 
at Ancestry, it's like search and hints of the  

630
00:49:44,080 --> 00:49:50,000
core. What is the mechanics? You want people 
to add people to their family tree. You want  

631
00:49:50,000 --> 00:49:54,640
them to add stories, okay? There's teams that 
make sure that the uptime is good, that the  

632
00:49:54,640 --> 00:49:58,880
hints are working, the search delivers results.
And you need those teams, you need those core  

633
00:49:58,880 --> 00:50:04,880
teams kind of functioning. But growth is actually 
optimization on top. It is making it so that  

634
00:50:04,880 --> 00:50:10,360
you get to the search flow faster. The hints are 
surfacing better, that people are accepting them,  

635
00:50:10,360 --> 00:50:14,760
that if we put the button here versus here, that 
people are going to discover things faster. And  

636
00:50:14,760 --> 00:50:21,000
so it's really taking the core engine and actually 
wrapping it around the user interface around the  

637
00:50:21,000 --> 00:50:25,880
experience, around the flows so that people can 
get to it faster, they can have more satisfaction,  

638
00:50:25,880 --> 00:50:30,880
they can have more impact. And that's what I see 
growth as. It's not the core product. It is the  

639
00:50:30,880 --> 00:50:37,520
cherry on top, making that product more accessible 
and more usable and better every single day.

640
00:50:37,520 --> 00:50:41,320
Along these lines, I think it surprised people 
to learn. There's at least a hundred people at  

641
00:50:41,320 --> 00:50:45,400
our Airbnb just working on pricing, 
optimizing pricing recommendations.  

642
00:50:45,400 --> 00:50:49,480
There's endless opportunity to just make 
all these core components of an experience  

643
00:50:49,480 --> 00:50:54,200
better and better and better over time. 
Okay. Last thing I want to talk about,  

644
00:50:54,200 --> 00:50:56,840
and this is completely unrelated to 
everything we've been talking about  

645
00:50:56,840 --> 00:51:02,600
mostly, which is your 30, 60, 90-day plan.
So you wrote this post a while ago, just like,  

646
00:51:02,600 --> 00:51:08,840
here's a great 30, 60, 90-day plan when 
you join a company. I've heard that many  

647
00:51:08,840 --> 00:51:12,840
people use this. It's really effective for 
helping someone onboard and be successful.  

648
00:51:12,840 --> 00:51:16,840
And I think it's mostly for execs or is 
this for just anyone joining a company?

649
00:51:16,840 --> 00:51:17,154
It's for anyone.

650
00:51:17,154 --> 00:51:18,520
Okay, anyone.

651
00:51:18,520 --> 00:51:23,800
I created, it's actually when I joined Ancestry 
because I hadn't started a real new job in 11  

652
00:51:23,800 --> 00:51:30,200
years. And I thought, I'm going to be a student 
of how to land well. So I read a bunch of things,  

653
00:51:30,200 --> 00:51:36,000
I read and I decided I was going to adapt all 
of those things into a summary and then I was  

654
00:51:36,000 --> 00:51:40,240
going to try it real time in my blog.
So in my blog I write, "Here's what I'm  

655
00:51:40,240 --> 00:51:44,480
going to do," and then I tell you what I did and 
how it worked and some things. And then I actually  

656
00:51:44,480 --> 00:51:52,280
do a look back as to all the mistakes I made. And 
so I did this live. It was not planned quite as  

657
00:51:52,280 --> 00:51:57,560
well as I would thought, but I put it together 
and I wrote the 30, 60, 90-day plan and I have  

658
00:51:57,560 --> 00:52:04,960
a template. I always tell people it's focused on 
listening and learning first and then doing. So  

659
00:52:04,960 --> 00:52:09,760
that's the crux of it, which is in those 90-days 
it's like you got to get used to the environment.  

660
00:52:09,760 --> 00:52:13,160
You want to have some impact at the start. You 
want to have a couple quick wins, but you want  

661
00:52:13,160 --> 00:52:19,720
to understand the lay of the land and you want to 
listen because you have something to contribute. 

662
00:52:19,720 --> 00:52:23,280
But if you don't understand the language, 
you don't understand the culture, you might  

663
00:52:23,280 --> 00:52:28,960
actually make huge mistakes. And so for the first 
30 days, I did a listening tour. I talked to over  

664
00:52:28,960 --> 00:52:34,840
60 people in 30 days and then I summarized a 
state of the union. Here's what I'm hearing,  

665
00:52:34,840 --> 00:52:39,000
here are the challenges people feel like we're 
facing. Here's what people's wishlists are.  

666
00:52:39,000 --> 00:52:43,120
And by the way, one person sent me a wishlist of 
five things and at that year, I think it took me  

667
00:52:43,120 --> 00:52:46,840
till year two to finish his five things. And 
then I sent him a note. I said, "By the way,  

668
00:52:46,840 --> 00:52:50,800
the first time we met, these five things you 
wanted to see, we just finished the last one." 

669
00:52:50,800 --> 00:52:54,720
And he's like, "I can't believe you remember." I 
took extensive notes and I summarized it. I think  

670
00:52:54,720 --> 00:53:01,240
it's important because people want to hear that 
you hear them. And you don't have to be a manager  

671
00:53:01,240 --> 00:53:06,360
or CEO to do that. I think people on teams often 
feel like there's no outlet for the things that  

672
00:53:06,360 --> 00:53:11,560
they want to say. I encourage, especially product 
leaders, especially if you're joining an existing  

673
00:53:11,560 --> 00:53:17,880
team, to listen really behind what people are 
saying and then offer to help them do one thing. 

674
00:53:17,880 --> 00:53:21,920
So especially when you're meeting with a new 
engineering team for the first time, actually  

675
00:53:21,920 --> 00:53:26,880
ask them, what is one thing I can do to help you 
this week? I always say one thing, it's limited.  

676
00:53:26,880 --> 00:53:32,200
This week, so getting 15 new headcount. Probably 
not going to happen. And it's like, how can I give  

677
00:53:32,200 --> 00:53:37,240
back? And suddenly you're building a reciprocal 
relationship. And so a lot of this 30, 60, 90-day  

678
00:53:37,240 --> 00:53:43,040
plan is really to help you find your footing 
and then to start having impact immediately.

679
00:53:43,040 --> 00:53:46,760
Say you join a company and you're like, 
"I'm going to do 30 days listening," and  

680
00:53:46,760 --> 00:53:49,600
then your boss is like, "No, we 
need to ship stuff. Get on it,  

681
00:53:49,600 --> 00:53:53,520
ship this stuff." Is there any advice for 
trying to push back on that, create space  

682
00:53:53,520 --> 00:53:57,480
for listening when there's deadlines, 
things aren't [inaudible 00:53:56]?

683
00:53:57,480 --> 00:54:01,760
I encourage everybody to get on the same page 
on this 30, 60, 90-day plan with their manager.  

684
00:54:01,760 --> 00:54:05,320
So actually don't just keep it to yourself. 
Share it with as many people as you can. So  

685
00:54:05,320 --> 00:54:08,920
I think it's very important that everyone sees 
what you're trying to accomplish and what your  

686
00:54:08,920 --> 00:54:13,520
output is going to be. Because if you don't 
know the output, is success there? The second  

687
00:54:13,520 --> 00:54:20,080
part is with your manager say, "Okay. I would 
like to carve 20% of my time listening and I'm  

688
00:54:20,080 --> 00:54:24,520
happy to do this work 80% of the time." 
Therefore every morning from nine to 10,  

689
00:54:24,520 --> 00:54:31,040
I want to talk to somebody in the organization.
Just make sure you say, "I will do a better job  

690
00:54:31,040 --> 00:54:36,520
and have more impact if I have this time to 
make sure that I'm not accidentally making  

691
00:54:36,520 --> 00:54:41,280
mistake or I don't get a chance, I'm asking 
something of somebody, but I've never met  

692
00:54:41,280 --> 00:54:46,560
them." And to really carve out space because 
it's really important. Once you're in it,  

693
00:54:47,280 --> 00:54:52,040
people give you the new person card for 
maybe a month or two and then suddenly  

694
00:54:52,040 --> 00:54:55,080
it's all the problems are your problems.
But what if you don't know what the problems  

695
00:54:55,080 --> 00:55:00,280
are? And so I always say diagnose before 
you treat. So make sure you understand so  

696
00:55:00,280 --> 00:55:04,360
that you can help and deliver what your 
manager is actually expecting of you.

697
00:55:04,360 --> 00:55:11,000
I'm looking at your template. So just to share the 
bucket. So first 30 days learning focus, second 30  

698
00:55:11,000 --> 00:55:16,760
days is aligning on vision for the future, and 
the last 30 days of the 90 days is executing,  

699
00:55:16,760 --> 00:55:23,760
setting up, actually starting to get stuff done. 
Awesome. Anything else along these lines of this?

700
00:55:23,760 --> 00:55:27,560
The one thing about having a plan 
also is that you don't feel rushed  

701
00:55:27,560 --> 00:55:32,760
to do something that you're not ready for 
because I do think sometimes you feel like  

702
00:55:32,760 --> 00:55:36,920
you need to have impact. I always 
tell people, "Do something small,  

703
00:55:36,920 --> 00:55:42,720
give back in some ways that people see you 
making." But when you actually reflect,  

704
00:55:42,720 --> 00:55:47,480
one of the biggest things I could do was actually 
reflect back to the organization, "Here's what I  

705
00:55:47,480 --> 00:55:52,960
heard from all of you. I'm listening, I hear 
this and here's what I want to do about it." 

706
00:55:52,960 --> 00:55:56,240
And then in aligning it's like, "Do we agree 
this is a set of problems we want to tackle?"  

707
00:55:56,760 --> 00:56:01,360
And then an execution is like, "Do we agree that 
this is how we want to move forward?" And I think  

708
00:56:01,360 --> 00:56:06,840
that is such an important part of building 
into a team. When you enter an organization,  

709
00:56:06,840 --> 00:56:11,600
you're also entering a team and you're part 
of a dance that's going around. What role do  

710
00:56:11,600 --> 00:56:15,920
you play? And people are dancing around you and 
if you actually make a mistake, you could trip  

711
00:56:15,920 --> 00:56:21,480
other people up as well. So really finding 
your place in the dance is really important.

712
00:56:21,480 --> 00:56:27,200
And as a PM, the way I always think about is 
people won't assume they should trust you.  

713
00:56:27,200 --> 00:56:32,280
You're just this person that's coming in to tell 
them what to do and so much of your first month,  

714
00:56:32,280 --> 00:56:36,760
two, three is building that trust with people 
so that they can actually feel comfortable  

715
00:56:36,760 --> 00:56:40,760
listening to your guidance and not just like, 
"Oh my god. This person is getting in my way."

716
00:56:40,760 --> 00:56:45,400
And earning that trust, sometimes people really... 
You'd be really surprised, a lot of people feel  

717
00:56:45,400 --> 00:56:50,920
like they're not heard and even just coming 
in and listening is a trust building exercise.

